# âœ… What is Constructor Chaining?

> Constructor chaining is the process where one constructor calls another constructor of the same class or its parent class.

This avoids code duplication and ensures proper initialization order.

---

## ðŸ”¹ Why Constructor Chaining is used

* Reuse initialization code
* Avoid duplicate logic
* Ensure consistent object setup
* Improve maintainability

---

# ðŸ”· Constructor Chaining in C++

## Types:

1. Within same class â†’ using initializer list
2. Base class constructor â†’ using `:` syntax

### âœ… Example (Same Class)

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {
    int age;
    string name;

public:
    Student() : Student(18, "Unknown") { }   // calls parameterized constructor

    Student(int a, string n) {
        age = a;
        name = n;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << age << " " << name << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.display();
}
```

### âœ… Output:

```
18 Unknown
```

---

# ðŸ”· Constructor Chaining in Java

Java uses:

* `this()` â†’ calls another constructor in same class
* `super()` â†’ calls parent constructor

### âœ… Example

```java
class Student {
    int age;
    String name;

    Student() {
        this(18, "Unknown");   // calls parameterized constructor
    }

    Student(int age, String name) {
        this.age = age;
        this.name = name;
    }
}
```

---

# ðŸ”· Constructor Chaining in C#

C# uses:

* `this()` â†’ same class constructor
* `base()` â†’ parent constructor

### âœ… Example

```csharp
class Student
{
    int age;
    string name;

    public Student() : this(18, "Unknown")
    {
    }

    public Student(int age, string name)
    {
        this.age = age;
        this.name = name;
    }
}
```

---

# âœ… Parent Constructor Chaining (Inheritance)

## Java / C#

```java
class Parent {
    Parent() {
        System.out.println("Parent");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        super();   // calls Parent constructor
        System.out.println("Child");
    }
}
```

## C#

```csharp
class Parent {
    public Parent() {
        Console.WriteLine("Parent");
    }
}

class Child : Parent {
    public Child() : base() {
        Console.WriteLine("Child");
    }
}
```

---

# ðŸ§  Execution Order

| Language | Same Class Keyword | Parent Keyword | Execution Order |
| -------- | ------------------ | -------------- | --------------- |
| C++      | Initializer List   | Base()         | Base â†’ Derived  |
| Java     | this()             | super()        | Parent â†’ Child  |
| C#       | this()             | base()         | Parent â†’ Child  |

---

# âœ… Interview Ready Comparison

| Language | Same Class Call          | Parent Call              |
| -------- | ------------------------ | ------------------------ |
| C++      | `: Constructor()` syntax | `Base()` via initializer |
| Java     | `this()`                 | `super()`                |
| C#       | `this()`                 | `base()`                 |

---

# âœ… Simple Definition

> Constructor chaining is when one constructor calls another constructor, either within the same class or from its base class, to reuse initialization logic.

---

# âœ… Real-Life Analogy

Imagine:

* Default constructor sets basic setup
* Parameter constructor does detailed setup
  Instead of repeating code, the default one calls the detailed one.

---

# Quick Cheat Sheet

| Language | Example                             |
| -------- | ----------------------------------- |
| C++      | `Student() : Student(10, "A") {}`   |
| Java     | `this(10,"A");`                     |
| C#       | `public Student(): this(10,"A") {}` |

